              <h4 class="text-light text-decoration-underline text-center pl-4 pr-4"><em><strong>Incorporate Vegetation Management Strategies</strong></em></h4>
              <p class="lead text-light text-center pl-4 pr-4"><em>Incorporating vegetation management strategies into civil engineering plans for flood-prone areas is a key part of mitigating the risks associated with flooding. <br>
                Vegetation can be used to slow and retain the flow of water, absorb floodwater, and even provide a buffer zone to protect against floods. <br>
                These strategies should be factored into the overall civil engineering plans for flood-prone areas and implemented in a way that maximizes the positive effects of vegetation on reducing flooding risks. <br>
                Furthermore, vegetation management strategies should be regularly monitored and adjusted as needed to ensure they remain effective. </em></p>
              <img src="images/navImg6.jpg" alt="navImg6">
              <hr>
              <h4 class="text-light text-decoration-underline text-center pl-4 pr-4"><strong><em>Create City-Level Infrastructure And Urban Planning Strategies</em></strong></h4>
              <p class="lead text-light text-center pl-4 pr-4"><em>Among the strategies for managing flood-prone areas is the development of city-level infrastructure and urban planning strategies. This includes the installation of stormwater systems and diversion systems. <br>
                Such infrastructure can reduce the risk of flooding by increasing the capacity of the city to manage stormwater runoff. Additionally, urban planning strategies can help reduce risk by ensuring that building codes are updated to account for changes in weather patterns and water levels. <br>
                Such strategies also involve assessing the vulnerability of existing infrastructure and identifying areas that are prone to flooding.</em></p>
